Hey! I noticed this little loop:

```js
for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
  total = total + arr[i];
}
```

A couple of tiny improvements you might enjoy:

1. Move the length lookup out of the condition  
   Each iteration the engine re-evaluates `arr.length`. It’s harmless for small arrays but unnecessary:
   ```js
   for (let i = 0, l = arr.length; i < l; i++) {
     total += arr[i];
   }
   ```

2. Consider `reduce` when the goal really is “sum every element”  
   ```js
   const total = arr.reduce((sum, n) => sum + n, 0);
   ```
   It’s declarative, avoids manual indexing, and works on any iterable.

3. Make sure `total` is initialized (I’m assuming it’s declared earlier).

Nothing broken—just small ways to tighten up and communicate intent more clearly.
